@node log1p
@section @code{log1p}, @code{log1pf}---log of @code{1 + @var{x}}
@findex log1p
@findex log1pf
@strong{Synopsis}
@example
#include <math.h>
double log1p(double @var{x});
float log1pf(float @var{x});

@end example
@strong{Description}@*
@code{log1p} calculates 
@tex
$ln(1+x)$, 
@end tex
the natural logarithm of @code{1+@var{x}}.  You can use @code{log1p} rather
than `@code{log(1+@var{x})}' for greater precision when @var{x} is very
small.

@code{log1pf} calculates the same thing, but accepts and returns
@code{float} values rather than @code{double}.

@*
@strong{Returns}@*
@code{log1p} returns a @code{double}, the natural log of @code{1+@var{x}}.
@code{log1pf} returns a @code{float}, the natural log of @code{1+@var{x}}.

@*
@strong{Portability}@*
Neither @code{log1p} nor @code{log1pf} is required by ANSI C or by the System V
Interface Definition (Issue 2).


@*
